jd brotherscontracting



Indeed these is a top tips that i read so far.It tells about the reality on how to market and to attract potential customers in all aspects.pretty awesome.






Judy Caroll



Great article. Well, I somehow see it difficult to generate leads in a solar company. But nevertheless, you have presented your ideas well in a way that you want it to be presented. Keep it up.






Rylan Urban



I think the ‘focus on customer’ should be emphasized here. The solar industry is turning into one where you need to provide real value to consumers in exchange for trust. Educational marketing is one way to do it – an approach that addresses the concern of the consumer by giving them the information that they need to know. This should be a whole point in and of itself. Something like what Solar Sell Marketing is doing






Kathy Heilmann



Great article but I don’t see how your illustration titled Custom Photovoltaic (PV) Systems supports your point about “no-name” vs. “Rolls-Royce” PV modules.  While high-end manufacturers like SunPower may be on the leading edge to produce the highest wattage modules, there is usually very little difference in the output of the total system because very few residential systems are roofspace constrained.  One extra module on the roof more than makes up for the difference between the top rating of SunPower vs. the top rating of one of the Chinese manufacturers who dominate market share today.
The real issue is long-term: will the more cheaply made Chinese modules have small manufacturing defects that show up as faster-than-expected degradation of output?  And if so, will they still be around and willing to stand behind their 25-year warranties?  That, plus a desire to “buy American” is the major reason to go with a higher-end, more expensive option like SunPower.






Matthew Hirsch



Kathy is right about the difference between Sunpower modules and Chinese modules. Module output is not as important as the value of the PV system as a whole. And it’s not true that more efficient modules always increase PV system value. Sometimes they do. Sometimes they don’t.
Residential installers should take note of marketing in the commercial space and adapt their message for homeowners. You don’t have to talk down to homeowners or appeal to the lowest common denominator. Give solid information to your customers, and you’ll get their attention in return.








plainview2



Zach: I follow the residential solar debate and development fairly closely but still could not tell you the “Roles Royce” or the most bang for the buck panel to consider.
When are you going to produce a consumer friendly report on the existing panels?






Matt



This could at best be a point in time report, or maybe a historically this company panels get a % rating. Since the panels are all still evolving and prices still dropping. But a general quality rating would be wonderful. I too could not tell a Yugo from a RR.












